column265: I was actually very cautious. I think I understood the experiment well  but the fact that the computer randomly chose which reward we would get made me very averse to decisions that could cause me to lose money. I generally started with half of my money in each asset and from there  I tried to ensure that my final amount would at least be over $3 while still putting as much money in asset A as possible.
It was well explained and the directions were easy to follow.
it was fun to say the least.  | the decisions were random for the most part.  | Thank you |
Just guessed! and every step was explained great
I was playing aroung with the bar to see the trends. I went along accordingly but was afriad of taking risks. I have not fully grasped the experiment.

I have never been great with numbers. I should have asked for a little more clarification on how one makes predictions based on the bar on the far right of the screen. A lot of it was guessing and hoping for good luck.
By probability and guessing. | How can someone always be rational without a certain probability?

The response time on screen had a bit of problem...the bars did not get activated as soon as I clicked on them. Also  in the 3rd set  i felt the 3 boxes during periods 5 & 9 were very distracting. Not enough time to see the box and then click the bar  adjusting the proportion of investment
it was disappointing that i got paid so little ):

I chose $20 as my "goal" because values below that were mostly inconsequential and values above that were too risky (because I might drop below $20). If I managed to hit $20 by investing 100% into asset A then I would only invest the money I had more than $20 into asset A.
